# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#  EDB Postgres® AI Blueprints — environment configuration
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Copy this file to `.env` and fill in values for the deploy target(s) you'll use.
# The agent reads `.env` at startup. Restart the agent after editing.
#
# Sections below are grouped by what controls what:
#   §1 AGENT LLM       — how the diab agent itself talks to Claude
#   §2 LAPTOP DEPLOY   — what's needed to deploy stacks on your laptop
#   §3 NORTHFLANK      — what's needed to deploy stacks to NF cloud
#   §4 BEDROCK FOR     — credentials passed into stack services (mlflow, langflow,
#      DEPLOYED STACKS   evaluation-runner) so they can call Bedrock at runtime
#   §5 OTHER           — port, API key, etc.
#   §6 AWS PROFILES    — terminal-only reference (not read by agent)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# §1  AGENT LLM CONFIGURATION
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# How the diab agent itself (chat / evaluation-runner) talks to Claude.
# Auto-detection order:
#   1. ANTHROPIC_API_KEY  (if set)
#   2. AWS_PROFILE        (if set)
#   3. AWS profiles named "Bedrock", "bedrock", "claude", "anthropic"
#   4. Default AWS credential chain (~/.aws/credentials, IAM role)
#
# For AWS SSO users:  aws sso login --profile Bedrock  (no env var needed).

# Option A — Direct Anthropic API
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...

# Option B — AWS Bedrock via named profile
# AWS_PROFILE=Bedrock
# AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1

# Option C — AWS Bedrock via access keys
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1

# Force a specific provider (overrides auto-detection)
# LLM_PROVIDER=anthropic
# LLM_PROVIDER=bedrock


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# §2  LAPTOP DEPLOY (Docker Desktop or Colima)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Needed only when deploying stacks to your laptop.
# Docker Desktop and Colima share the same Docker daemon → same vars.

# EDB Repos 2.0 token — required to build the pgd image (BFSI's custom EDB
# Postgres image pulls EDB packages from docker.enterprisedb.com).
# Get from: https://www.enterprisedb.com/repos-downloads
# EDB_SUBSCRIPTION_TOKEN=


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# §3  NORTHFLANK DEPLOY TARGET
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Needed only when deploying stacks to NF cloud.
# All values from NF Console — no defaults; agent errors clearly if missing.

# NF API token, scoped to the project (Account settings → API tokens)
# NORTHFLANK_API_KEY=

# Team slug — the path segment after /t/ in NF Console URL
# https://app.northflank.com/t/<TEAM>/project/<PROJECT>
# NORTHFLANK_TEAM=

# Project ID — the path segment after /project/ in NF Console URL
# NORTHFLANK_PROJECT=

# Compute plan applied to NF deployment services (e.g. nf-compute-20,
# nf-compute-50, nf-compute-100, nf-compute-200). Check NF Console → Billing.
# NORTHFLANK_BILLING_PLAN=nf-compute-20

# Team-level registry integration ID for pulling private images on NF.
# Set up once in NF Console → team → Integrations → Registries → Add new.
#   - Provider: github (for GHCR), ecr, dockerhub, etc.
#   - Username + token with read:packages (GHCR) or equivalent.
# Put the integration's ID/name (not the PAT) here.
# Agent attaches it to deploys whose image starts with GHCR_PREFIX.
# Public images (postgres, nginx, etc.) skip the credential.
# NORTHFLANK_REGISTRY_CREDENTIALS=

# Container registry prefix for stacks that build: their images locally.
# Build images locally, push to this registry, NF pulls from it during deploy.
# Examples:
#   GHCR_PREFIX=ghcr.io/<your-username>/diab-bfsi
#   GHCR_PREFIX=<acct>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/diab-bfsi
# If unset, build: services are skipped during NF deploy.
# GHCR_PREFIX=


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# §4  BEDROCK CREDENTIALS FOR DEPLOYED STACK SERVICES
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Passed as runtime env vars into BFSI services that call Bedrock at runtime:
# mlflow (AI Gateway), langflow (visual agent), evaluation-runner.
#
# DIFFERENT from §1 above — §1 is for the diab agent's own LLM calls,
# §4 is what gets injected into deployed services so THEY can call Bedrock.
#
# How to populate:
#   aws sso login --profile Bedrock
#   aws --profile Bedrock configure export-credentials --format env
# Then paste the values into the three lines below, renaming the keys:
#   AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID       → AWS_BEDROCK_ACCESS_KEY_ID
#   AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY   → AWS_BEDROCK_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
#   AWS_SESSION_TOKEN       → AWS_BEDROCK_SESSION_TOKEN
#
# Session-scoped — expire every 8-12 hrs. Re-run + paste when expired.

# AWS_BEDROCK_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_BEDROCK_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# AWS_BEDROCK_SESSION_TOKEN=
# AWS_BEDROCK_REGION=us-east-1


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# §5  OTHER SETTINGS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# Chat UI port (default 4000, since PeerDB uses 3000)
# PORT=4000

# API key for protected endpoints (auto-generated if not set)
# AGENT_API_KEY=your-secret-key

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   Stack-specific tuning
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Per-stack resource knobs (pgd memory, corpus sizes, batch sizes, etc.) live
# in each stack's stack.yaml under `tuning.profiles`, not here. Each stack
# ships small/medium/large/xl profiles tuned for its services.
#
# Override an individual value at deploy time by setting it directly in this
# file — it wins over the profile defaults. Examples:
#   PGD_MEMORY_LIMIT=6g
#   HYBRID_BM25_CORPUS=5000
# Full var list per stack: stacks/<name>/stack.yaml → tuning.profiles


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# §6  AWS PROFILES — TERMINAL USE ONLY (agent does not read these)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Reference list — these profiles live in ~/.aws/config. The agent only reads
# AWS_PROFILE (§1 above) and the AWS_BEDROCK_* vars (§4 above).
#
#   edb-eks   → BYOC EKS cluster operations (CORP-RUNBOOK.md scaling/teardown)
#   Bedrock   → source for §4 credentials
#
# Setup steps for both profiles:  k8s-work/eks/CORP-RUNBOOK.md  "AWS CLI profile setup"
